      <ul><br><br>
        <p class="MB_Heading">Editorials</p>
        <ul>
          <p class="MB_SubHead">2. The Monkly Race Question:</p>
          <ul>
            <p class="MB_Body"> 
              <p>
Monks can be either Human or Iksar (a reptilian race). Which is better?  It depends.
</p>
<p>
Human monks can't see in the dark, 
</p>
<p>
However, they do more damage than Iksar in the long run, 
</p>
<p>Have more strength,
</p>
<p>More endurance (stamina),
</p>
<p>can wear some plate-based items,
</p>
<p>and can enter most cities with impunity (depending on religious affiliation and faction hits). 

</p>
<p>
Iksar start with the disadvantages of horrible faction (Kill On Sight in most cities), 
and inability to wear plate-based armor; 
</p>
<p>
while benefiting from innate night-vision, 
</p>
<p>better Armor Class (AC), 
</p>
<p>regeneration ability, 
</p>
<p>forage skill, 
</p>
<p>newbie quests with relatively decent gear, 
</p>
<p>and improved swimming skill. 

</p>
<p>
To quote Abashi AKA Gordon Winn, "Iksar monks won't be as good at being monks as humans. It's not by a large margin, but humans will still deal more damage at a given level than Iksar. The purpose of this is to further offset the other advantages available to the Iksar. Remember, Iksar monks are the only race/class combo that gets AC bonuses for both race and class."
Abashi was full of fertilizer.  It turns out that Iksar are actually somewhat better monks that humans.  The natural regeneration, infravision, foraging ability, and armor bonus more than offset the experience point penalty, attack delay penalty, and KOS problem.  The inability to wear plate-based armor is not a problem, as, except for a couple of unique items, monks cannot wear plate armor anyway.  KOS problems can be overcome with a lot of faction work; although Cazic Thule haters will always hate them.
</p>
          </ul>
        </ul>
        <p class="MB_Submit">If you would like to submit an article to the site, 
